{"type":"text","timestamp":1775851117145,"sessionID":"ses_287070c89ffe3khl0ITOaSaTIo","part":{"id":"prt_d78f99742001cnuFMIIXWEFbqk","messageID":"msg_d78f987c5001BifjzMQL3Rpf2E","sessionID":"ses_287070c89ffe3khl0ITOaSaTIo","type":"text","text":"Now I understand the format. Let me write the delta-spec.md for AR-011 (Router JWT Authentication) following the same OpenSpec format with GIVEN/WHEN/THEN scenarios:","time":{"start":1775851117143,"end":1775851117143}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775851190671,"sessionID":"ses_287070c89ffe3khl0ITOaSaTIo","part":{"id":"prt_d78f99a5a001HO1Eqqe1QXEKxY","messageID":"msg_d78f987c5001BifjzMQL3Rpf2E","sessionID":"ses_287070c89ffe3khl0ITOaSaTIo","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bf478757d49e4de8a4053ea6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/router/delta-spec.md","content":"# Delta Specification: AR-011 — Router JWT Authentication & Issuance\n\n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Type:** New Feature\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThis specification defines JWT authentication and token issuance functionality for the AgentCube router module. The router will validate incoming JWT tokens for protected endpoints and provide token issuance capabilities using Kubernetes service accounts for credential verification.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### R-1: JWT Token Validation\n\n**Given** a request arrives at a protected endpoint  \n**When** the request contains a JWT token in the Authorization header  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Extract the token from the `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header\n- Validate the token signature using the configured secret key\n- Verify token expiration (`exp` claim)\n- Validate issuer (`iss`) and audience (`aud`) claims\n- Parse and attach claims to the request context\n- Allow the request to proceed to the handler if valid\n- Return HTTP 401 Unauthorized if invalid\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Valid JWT token allows request\n  Given a valid JWT token signed with the configured secret key\n  And the token has not expired\n  And the issuer and audience claims match configuration\n  When a request with \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\" is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the token signature SHALL be validated successfully\n  And the token expiration SHALL be verified\n  And the claims SHALL be extracted and attached to request context\n  And the request SHALL proceed to the handler\n  And HTTP 200 OK SHALL be returned by the handler\n\nScenario: Invalid token signature rejects request\n  Given a JWT token signed with an incorrect secret key\n  When a request with the invalid token is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the signature validation SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"invalid token signature\"\n\nScenario: Expired token rejects request\n  Given a JWT token with exp claim in the past\n  When a request with the expired token is received\n  Then the expiration check SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"token expired\"\n\nScenario: Missing Authorization header rejects request\n  Given no Authorization header in the request\n  When a request is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"missing authorization header\"\n\nScenario: Malformed Authorization header rejects request\n  Given an Authorization header not starting with \"Bearer \"\n  When a request is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"invalid authorization format\"\n\nScenario: Invalid issuer claim rejects request\n  Given a JWT token with iss claim not matching configuration\n  When a request with the token is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the issuer validation SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"invalid issuer\"\n\nScenario: Invalid audience claim rejects request\n  Given a JWT token with aud claim not matching configuration\n  When a request with the token is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the audience validation SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"invalid audience\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-2: JWT Token Issuance\n\n**Given** a token request endpoint `/api/v1/auth/token`  \n**When** a POST request with valid credentials is received  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Verify credentials against Kubernetes service account or configured auth source\n- Use client-go to validate service account existence if using K8s auth\n- Generate a JWT token with appropriate claims\n- Sign the token with the configured secret key\n- Return the token in the response body\n- Set appropriate token expiration\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Token issued with valid service account credentials\n  Given a valid Kubernetes ServiceAccount \"agent-runner\" in namespace \"default\"\n  And a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/token\" with service account token\n  When the credentials are verified successfully\n  Then a JWT token SHALL be generated\n  And the token SHALL include user_id claim set to the service account name\n  And the token SHALL include role claim set to \"agent\"\n  And the token SHALL include tenant_id claim set to the namespace\n  And the token SHALL be signed with the configured secret key\n  And the response SHALL contain the token with HTTP 200 OK\n\nScenario: Token issuance fails with invalid credentials\n  Given non-existent service account credentials\n  When a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/token\" is received\n  Then credential verification SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And no token SHALL be issued\n\nScenario: Token includes correct expiration\n  Given token expiration is configured to 3600 seconds\n  When a token is issued\n  Then the token exp claim SHALL be set to current time + 3600 seconds\n  And the response SHALL include the expiration time\n\nScenario: Token request with missing credentials\n  Given a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/token\" without credentials\n  When the request is received\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 400 Bad Request\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"missing credentials\"\n\nScenario: Token request with disabled issuance\n  Given token issuance is disabled in configuration\n  When a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/token\" is received\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"token issuance disabled\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-3: Token Refresh\n\n**Given** a valid JWT token with refresh capability  \n**When** a refresh request is received at `/api/v1/auth/refresh`  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Validate the existing token\n- Generate a new token with updated expiration\n- Preserve original claims (user_id, role, tenant_id)\n- Return the new token\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Token refresh with valid token\n  Given a valid JWT token that is not expired\n  When a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/refresh\" is received with the token\n  Then the token SHALL be validated\n  And a new token SHALL be issued with same claims\n  And the new token SHALL have updated expiration\n  And HTTP 200 OK SHALL be returned with the new token\n\nScenario: Token refresh with expired token\n  Given an expired JWT token\n  When a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/refresh\" is received\n  Then the refresh SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"cannot refresh expired token\"\n\nScenario: Token refresh disabled\n  Given refresh is disabled in JWT configuration\n  When a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/refresh\" is received\n  Then the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"refresh disabled\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-4: JWT Configuration\n\n**Given** the router starts up  \n**When** JWT configuration is loaded  \n**Then** the following settings SHALL be configurable:\n- Secret key for signing (required, from environment variable or file)\n- Token expiration duration (default: 1 hour)\n- Issuer claim value (default: \"agentcube-router\")\n- Audience claim value (default: \"agentcube-services\")\n- Refresh enabled flag (default: true)\n- Auth method (serviceaccount | config | none)\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Load JWT config from environment variables\n  Given environment variables JWT_SECRET, JWT_EXPIRY, JWT_ISSUER are set\n  When the router initializes\n  Then the configuration SHALL be loaded from environment\n  And the values SHALL be applied to JWT validation\n\nScenario: JWT config missing secret key\n  Given JWT_SECRET environment variable is not set\n  When the router initializes\n  Then initialization SHALL fail\n  And an error SHALL be returned indicating \"missing JWT secret\"\n\nScenario: JWT config with invalid expiry duration\n  Given JWT_EXPIRY is set to a non-duration string\n  When the router initializes\n  Then the default expiry (1 hour) SHALL be used\n  And a warning SHALL be logged\n\nScenario: JWT config from file\n  Given a JWT config file at /etc/agentcube/jwt-config.yaml\n  When the router initializes\n  Then the configuration SHALL be loaded from the file\n  And environment variables SHALL override file config\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-5: Middleware Integration\n\n**Given** a router instance with registered routes  \n**When** JWT middleware is configured  \n**Then** the middleware SHALL:\n- Protect specified routes with JWT validation\n- Allow bypass for configured public paths\n- Extract and validate tokens from Authorization header\n- Attach claims to request context for downstream handlers\n- Skip validation for paths in the skip list\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Protected route requires valid token\n  Given JWT middleware is registered for \"/api/v1/agents/*\"\n  And a request is received at \"/api/v1/agents/list\" without token\n  When the request is processed\n  Then the middleware SHALL validate the token\n  And return HTTP 401 Unauthorized due to missing token\n\nScenario: Public path bypasses authentication\n  Given \"/healthz\" is in the skip paths list\n  When a request is received at \"/healthz\" without token\n  Then the middleware SHALL skip validation\n  And the request SHALL proceed to the handler\n\nScenario: Claims attached to request context\n  Given a valid JWT token with user_id=\"agent-1\" and role=\"admin\"\n  When a request with the token is processed by middleware\n  Then the claims SHALL be attached to request context\n  And downstream handlers SHALL access claims via context\n\nScenario: Multiple routes with different protection levels\n  Given some routes are protected and others are public\n  When requests are received at both route types\n  Then protected routes SHALL require valid tokens\n  And public routes SHALL allow unauthenticated access\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-6: Kubernetes Client Integration\n\n**Given** authentication method is set to \"serviceaccount\"  \n**When** validating credentials for token issuance  \n**Then** the router SHALL use client-go to:\n- Create a clientset using `clientset.NewForConfig(config)`\n- Use `CoreV1().ServiceAccounts(namespace)` to verify service account existence\n- Optionally use `AgentRuntimeInterface` to verify agent runtime permissions\n- Cache service account lookups to reduce API server load\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Verify service account exists using client-go\n  Given ServiceAccount \"agent-runner\" exists in namespace \"default\"\n  When credentials are validated with this service account\n  Then the router SHALL use CoreV1().ServiceAccounts(\"default\").Get()\n  And the service account SHALL be verified as existing\n  And token issuance SHALL proceed\n\nScenario: Service account does not exist\n  Given ServiceAccount \"non-existent\" does not exist in namespace \"default\"\n  When credentials are validated with this service account\n  Then the client-go call SHALL return NotFound error\n  And token issuance SHALL fail with HTTP 401\n\nScenario: Clientset connection failure\n  Given Kubernetes API server is unreachable\n  When credential validation is attempted\n  Then the clientset call SHALL fail\n  And the router SHALL return HTTP 503 Service Unavailable\n  And the error SHALL indicate API server connection issue\n\nScenario: Use informer for service account caching\n  Given the router is running with service account informers\n  When multiple credential validations occur for same service account\n  Then the informer cache SHALL be used for lookups\n  And API server calls SHALL be minimized\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-7: Token Blacklist / Revocation\n\n**Given** a token revocation mechanism is required  \n**When** a token needs to be revoked before expiration  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Maintain a token blacklist in memory or Redis\n- Check blacklisted tokens during validation\n- Provide endpoint to revoke tokens\n- Clean up expired entries from blacklist\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Revoke token via API\n  Given a valid JWT token exists\n  When a POST request to \"/api/v1/auth/revoke\" is received with the token\n  Then the token's JTI SHALL be added to the blacklist\n  And HTTP 200 OK SHALL be returned\n  And subsequent requests with the token SHALL be rejected\n\nScenario: Blacklisted token is rejected\n  Given a token's JTI is in the blacklist\n  When a request with the token is received at a protected endpoint\n  Then the middleware SHALL check the blacklist\n  And return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n  And the response body SHALL indicate \"token revoked\"\n\nScenario: Blacklist cleanup expired entries\n  Given blacklist contains expired entries\n  When the cleanup interval triggers (default: 1 hour)\n  Then expired entries SHALL be removed from the blacklist\n  And memory usage SHALL be reduced\n```\n\n---\n\n### R-8: Logging and Audit\n\n**Given** the router handles authentication events  \n**When** authentication operations occur  \n**Then** the router SHALL:\n- Log all token validation attempts with result\n- Log all token issuance events\n- Log authentication failures with reason\n- Include request ID, user ID, and timestamp in audit logs\n- Not log sensitive token values\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios:**\n\n```gherkin\nScenario: Log successful authentication\n  Given a request with valid token is processed\n  When authentication succeeds\n  Then an INFO log SHALL be written\n  And the log SHALL include user_id, method, path, and duration\n  And the token value SHALL NOT be logged\n\nScenario: Log authentication failure\n  Given a request with invalid token is processed\n  When authentication fails\n  Then a WARN log SHALL be written\n  And the log SHALL include failure reason (expired, invalid signature, etc.)\n  And the token value SHALL NOT be logged\n\nScenario: Log token issuance\n  Given a token is successfully issued\n  When the issuance completes\n  Then an INFO log SHALL be written\n  And the log SHALL include user_id and tenant_id\n  And the issued token SHALL NOT be logged\n```\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Usage |\n|------------|--------|-------|\n| `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | External | JWT parsing and signing |\n| `k8s.io/client-go` | `client-go/` | Service account validation |\n| `k8s.io/api/core/v1` | External | ServiceAccount type |\n| `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` | Generated | AgentRuntime client (optional) |\n\n---\n\n## Data Structures\n\n### JWTConfig\n\n```go\ntype JWTConfig struct {\n    SecretKey      string        `json:\"-\" yaml:\"-\"` // Signing secret (never logged)\n    Expiration     time.Duration `json:\"expiration\" yaml:\"expiration\"`\n    Issuer         string        `json:\"issuer\" yaml:\"issuer\"`\n    Audience       string        `json:\"audience\" yaml:\"audience\"`\n    RefreshEnabled bool          `json:\"refresh_enabled\" yaml:\"refresh_enabled\"`\n    AuthMethod     string        `json:\"auth_method\" yaml:\"auth_method\"` // serviceaccount|config|none\n}\n```\n\n### TokenClaims\n\n```go\ntype TokenClaims struct {\n    jwt.RegisteredClaims\n    UserID   string `json:\"user_id\"`\n    Role     string `json:\"role\"`\n    TenantID string `json:\"tenant_id,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n### TokenRequest\n\n```go\ntype TokenRequest struct {\n    ServiceAccount string `json:\"service_account,omitempty\"`\n    Namespace      string `json:\"namespace,omitempty\"`\n    Token          string `json:\"token,omitempty\"` // For token-based auth\n}\n```\n\n### TokenResponse\n\n```go\ntype TokenResponse struct {\n    Token     string    `json:\"token\"`\n    ExpiresAt time.Time `json:\"expires_at\"`\n    TokenType string    `json:\"token_type\"`\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Interfaces\n\n### JWTAuthenticator\n\n```go\ntype JWTAuthenticator interface {\n    Validate(token string) (*TokenClaims, error)\n    Issue(claims TokenClaims) (string, error)\n    Refresh(token string) (string, error)\n    Revoke(token string) error\n}\n```\n\n### Middleware Factory\n\n```go\nfunc JWTMiddleware(auth JWTAuthenticator, skipPaths ...string) gin.HandlerFunc\n```\n\n---\n\n## Files to Create/Modify\n\n| File | Action | Description |\n|------|--------|-------------|\n| `pkg/router/auth/jwt.go` | Create | JWT authentication implementation |\n| `pkg/router/auth/config.go` | Create | JWT configuration structures |\n| `pkg/router/auth/config_loader.go` | Create | Configuration loading from env/file |\n| `pkg/router/middleware/auth.go` | Create | Gin middleware for JWT |\n| `pkg/router/handlers/token.go` | Create | Token issuance/refresh handlers |\n| `pkg/router/handlers/revoke.go` | Create | Token revocation handler |\n| `pkg/router/blacklist/blacklist.go` | Create | Token blacklist management |\n| `pkg/router/router.go` | Modify | Add middleware registration |\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n1. **Unit Tests**: \n   - Mock JWT signing/validation with test keys\n   - Test all validation failure modes\n   - Test configuration loading\n\n2. **Integration Tests**: \n   - Use fake clientset for service account validation\n   - Test token issuance with mock credentials\n   - Test middleware with test HTTP server\n\n3. **E2E Tests**: \n   - Deploy to test cluster with real ServiceAccounts\n   - Test full authentication flow\n   - Test token refresh and revocation\n\n---\n\n## Security Considerations\n\n- **Secret Key Storage**: Must be loaded from environment variable or secure file (never committed)\n- **Token Logging**: Token values MUST NOT be logged\n- **HTTPS Required**: JWT tokens must only be transmitted over HTTPS\n- **Short Expiration**: Default token expiration should be <= 1 hour\n- **Blacklist**: Support immediate token revocation for security incidents\n- **RBAC**: Router service account requires permissions to get ServiceAccounts\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Should JWT tokens support custom claims for agent-specific metadata?\n2. Should the blacklist be backed by Redis for multi-instance deployments?\n3. Should OAuth2/OIDC integration be supported in addition to service accounts?\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/router/delta-spec.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/router/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775851190656,"end":1775851190667}}}}
